Machine Learning Exploration of Canadian Cheeses#

Introduction#

In this project, I explored the cheese dataset from Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada to investigate the question: which model - Decision Tree, KNN, RBF SVM, Random Forest, Logistic Regression - best predicts Canadian cheese fat level based on features: ‘ManufacturerProvCode’, ‘ManufacturingTypeEn’, MoisturePercent’, ‘FlavourEn’, ‘Organic’, ‘CategoryTypeEn’ and ‘MilkTypeEn’. This was a classification problem, as the output is one of two categories: “lower fat” or “higher fat”. The positive label was column “FatLevel”.

Data Visualization#

As part of my exploratory data analysis, I made several visualizations to see the impact of certain features on the fat content.

# Plot a histogram demonstrating the distribution of moisture content and how this relates to the fat level of a cheese
moisture_histogram = alt.Chart(cheese_df_full).mark_bar(
        opacity=0.7).encode(
        alt.X("MoisturePercent", bin=alt.Bin(maxbins=50)),
        alt.Y('count()', stack=True),
        alt.Color('FatLevel:N')).properties(
        title="Figure 1. MoisturePercent Histogram")
moisture_histogram

It looks like the higher moisture percentage cheeses are lower fat, while higher fat cheeses make up a greater proportion of the lower moisture percentage cheeses.

# What about the cheese count and fat level by province? I put the provinces in geographical order on the x-axis, west to east.
moisture_province = alt.Chart(cheese_df_full).mark_bar().encode(
        alt.X("ManufacturerProvCode", sort=["BC", "AB", "MB", "SK", "ON", "QC", "NB", "PE", "NS", "NL"]),
        alt.Y("count()", stack = True),
        alt.Color('FatLevel:N')).properties(
        title="Figure 2. Cheese count, fat level by Province")
moisture_province

From this bar chart, I could see that Quebec produces, by far, the greatest number of cheeses, and that the majority of these cheeses are lower fat. The other provinces of note are Ontario and BC, though they produce far fewer cheeses than Quebec. The proportion of higher fat to lower fat cheeses in these top three cheese producing provinces seems (by eye) about similar.

Missing Data and Value Counts#

Next, I examined the dataframe, to see if there are any values missing. Then I ran value_counts() on the different categorical column types that I am interested in using in my analysis (ManufacturerProvCode, ManufacturingTypeEn, CategoryTypeEn, MilkTypeEn, MilkTreatmentTypeEn) to see how many different entries are present in each, and whether these columns have binary data or not. For example, the MilkTreatmentType column only has two different values in the top 20 rows that I examined earlier (Raw Milk and Pasteurized) - but I needed to see which different values are present in the entire column to check if this is a binary column, or a categorical column.

Methods & Results#

First, I removed the columns that I will not be using for my analysis: “CharacteristicsEn” and “RindTypeEn”. I removed these columns because they have around 40-50% of data missing, and because visual inspection suggests that the data may not be very meaningful for our analysis (ie. the CharacteristicsEn column has a wide variety of cheese descriptors, from information that may be found on the cheese label, to flavour descriptors, to information regarding whether the cheese is organic or not. This information can be found in other columns, and so can be removed.)

cheese_df = cheese_df_full.drop(columns=["CharacteristicsEn", "RindTypeEn"])

Train and test splits#

Now, before doing anything else, I split my data into train and test splits, with a test size of 20%. I created my X_train and X_test dataframes by dropping column “FatLevel” and made this my target column in my y_train and y_test dataframes.

cheese_df['FlavourEn'] = cheese_df['FlavourEn'].fillna(value="missing")

train_df, test_df = train_test_split(cheese_df, test_size = 0.2)

X_train, y_train = train_df.drop(columns = ["FatLevel"]), train_df["FatLevel"]
X_test, y_test = test_df.drop(columns = ["FatLevel"]), test_df["FatLevel"]

Model features#

There are numeric, categorical, binary and text features in my dataframe. I created lists for each of these categories, so that I could perform the correct transformations on each.

numeric_features = ["MoisturePercent"]
categorical_features = ["ManufacturerProvCode", "ManufacturingTypeEn", "CategoryTypeEn", "MilkTypeEn", "MilkTreatmentTypeEn"]

# I've created a list of drop features, but these will anyway by default be passed through with no transformation if they don't appear in the other transformers (numerical, categorical or binary)
drop_features = ["CheeseId", "CheeseName"]
binary_features = ["Organic"]
text_features = "FlavourEn"

I made different transformers to handle all of these different data types, imputing and scaling on each type. In the case of the binary transformer, I added a SimpleImputer, even though no values are missing. I did this in case data is added to the dataframe in the future, with missing values for this column.

numerical_transformer = make_pipeline(SimpleImputer(strategy="median"), StandardScaler())
categorical_transformer = make_pipeline(SimpleImputer(strategy="most_frequent"), OneHotEncoder(dtype="int", handle_unknown="ignore"))
binary_transformer = make_pipeline(SimpleImputer(strategy="most_frequent"), OneHotEncoder(dtype="int", drop="if_binary"))
text_transformer = make_pipeline(CountVectorizer())

Then I made a column transformer to handle all of the different type of data. Not specified columns were dropped. I wanted to see whether or not adding the text features (found in column “FlavourEn”) results a better model or not. I therefore chose to perform two fits, one with text features, and one without.

preprocessor_text = make_column_transformer((numerical_transformer, numeric_features),(categorical_transformer, categorical_features),(binary_transformer, binary_features),(text_transformer, text_features))
preprocessor_notext = make_column_transformer((numerical_transformer, numeric_features),(categorical_transformer, categorical_features),(binary_transformer, binary_features))

preprocessor_dict = {
    "Preprocessor (text)": preprocessor_text,
    "Preprocessor (no text)": preprocessor_notext,
}

Scorers#

The next step in my analysis was to create a baseline (dummy) model. I used the make_scorer function to create functions for precision, recall and f1. This was necessary, as my output column was “FatLevel” with values “higher fat” and “lower fat”. I needed to tell these scoring functions that my pos_label is “higher fat”.

precision_scorer_cheese = make_scorer(score_func = precision_score, pos_label = "higher fat")
recall_scorer_cheese =make_scorer(score_func = recall_score, pos_label = "higher fat")
f1_scorer_cheese = make_scorer(score_func = f1_score, pos_label = "higher fat")

I reated a scoring dictionary to score each of my models on accuracy, precision, recall and f1.

scoring_dict = {"accuracy": "accuracy",
                "precision": precision_scorer_cheese,
                "recall": recall_scorer_cheese,
                "f1": f1_scorer_cheese,
               }

Baseline Model - Dummy Classifier#

I started by creating a DummyClassifier, using strategy “stratified”, as my baseline model. In “stratified”, skikitlearn states that the “predict_proba method randomly samples one-hot vectors from a multinomial distribution parametrized by the empirical class prior probabilities” - this is the strategy to use, given that our problem is a classification problem with two categorical values: “higher fat” or “lower fat”.

Later, I compared the scores of my other classifiers to the DummyClassifier score I obtain below.

# Let's start with the DummyClassifier
Dummy_model = DummyClassifier(strategy = "stratified", random_state=123)
cv_scores = cross_validate(Dummy_model, X_train, y_train, cv = 5, return_train_score=True, scoring=scoring_dict)
dummy_scores = pd.DataFrame(cv_scores)

Testing Models#

I decided to use a function, test_models, to test five different models (Decision Tree, kNN, RBF SVM, Random Forest and Logistic Regression). I then checked the train and validation accuracies and f1_scores of these models to determine which are the top three. Next, I performed hyperparameter tuning on the top three models.

results_dict = {'Dummy': {'mean_train_accuracy': round(dummy_scores["train_accuracy"].mean(),4),
                          'mean_validation_accuracy': round(dummy_scores["test_accuracy"].mean(),4),
                          'mean_train_f1': round(dummy_scores["test_f1"].mean(),4),
                          'mean_validation_f1': round(dummy_scores["train_f1"].mean(),4)}}

model_dict = {
    "Decision Tree": DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight="balanced", random_state=123),
    "kNN": KNeighborsClassifier(),
    "RBF SVM": SVC(class_weight="balanced", random_state=123),
    "Random Forest": RandomForestClassifier(class_weight="balanced", random_state=123),
    "Logistic Regression": LogisticRegression(class_weight="balanced", random_state=123),
}

def test_models(preprocessor_dict, model_dict):

    for model_name, model in model_dict.items():
        for preprocessor_name, preprocessor in preprocessor_dict.items():
            
            pipe = make_pipeline(preprocessor, model)
    
            scores = cross_validate(pipe, X_train, y_train, cv=5, return_train_score=True, scoring=scoring_dict)
        
            #print(model_name, pd.DataFrame(scores))
    
            results_dict[model_name + " using " + preprocessor_name] ={'mean_train_accuracy': scores["train_accuracy"].mean().round(4),
                        'mean_validation_accuracy': scores["test_accuracy"].mean().round(4),
                        'mean_train_f1': scores["test_f1"].mean().round(4),
                        'mean_validation_f1': scores["train_f1"].mean().round(4)
                              }
        
    return pd.DataFrame(results_dict).T
    
test_models(preprocessor_dict, model_dict)

Adding the “FlavourEn” column did not improve accuracy, but improved f1_score. I therefore kept text features in my model, as I got a very high validation f1_score when I considered their contribution to the prediction.

The three models I continued my analysis with were: Decision Tree, kNN and Random Forest. At the moment, the Random Forest model scored highest, but I wanted to see whether or not the other models could perform better following hyperparameter tuning. I used f1_score (using my function “f1_scorer_cheese”) as the score to optimize.

Hyperparameter tuning on top three models#

Because I decided to only tune two parameters per model, I used GridSearchCV (not RandomizedSearchCV).

Decision Tree Tuning#

# Hyperparameter tuning to tune the DecisionTreeClassifier

dt_pipeline = make_pipeline(preprocessor_text, DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight="balanced", random_state=123))

param_dist = {
    "decisiontreeclassifier__max_depth": [None] + list(range(2,21)),
    "decisiontreeclassifier__min_samples_split": list(range(2,21))
}

dt_grid_search = GridSearchCV(
    dt_pipeline,
    param_dist,
    cv=5,
    verbose=1,
    n_jobs=-1,
    scoring=f1_scorer_cheese,
)
    
dt_grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

Just out of curiosity, I checked to see how much the hyperparameter tuning improved my model. I created one pipe with the preprocessor_text, and the standard RandomForestClassifier, with default parameters. I then checked to see what the f1_scores were for this default Random Forest classifier.

default_rf_pipe = make_pipeline(preprocessor_text, RandomForestClassifier(class_weight="balanced", random_state=123))
default_rf_pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)

default_rf_score_train = default_rf_pipe.score(X_train, y_train)
default_rf_score_test = default_rf_pipe.score(X_test, y_test)
print("Default RF training score (ie. accuracy):", default_rf_score_train, "and Default RF testing score (ie. accuracy):", default_rf_score_test)

Default RF training score (ie. accuracy): 0.9915966386554622 and Default RF testing score (ie. accuracy): 0.8038277511961722

# What about f1 score?
y_predict_train = default_rf_pipe.predict(X_train)
f1_score_train = f1_score(y_true=y_train, y_pred=y_predict_train, pos_label = "higher fat")

y_predict_test = default_rf_pipe.predict(X_test)
f1_score_test = f1_score(y_true=y_test, y_pred=y_predict_test, pos_label = "higher fat")

print("Default RF f1 score, training:", f1_score_train, "and Default RF f1 score, testing:", f1_score_test)

Default RF f1 score, training: 0.9875222816399287 and Default RF f1 score, testing: 0.7092198581560284

It looks like the training f1 score was higher for the default Random Forest Classifier (0.9845 vs. 0.9517 for the hyperparameter tuned model), but the score on the testing data set was worse (0.7273 vs. 0.7632 for the hyperparameter tuned model).

Discussion#

My project aimed to find which model - Decision Tree, KNN, LogisticRegression - best predicts Canadian cheese fat level based on features: ‘ManufacturerProvCode’, ‘ManufacturingTypeEn’, MoisturePercent’, ‘FlavourEn’, ‘Organic’, ‘CategoryTypeEn’ and ‘MilkTypeEn’.

Ultimately, I found that a Random Forest model performs the best, although the performance is still not very good, with an f1 score of 0.7632 on the test data.

While completing this assignment, out of curiosity I looked at building a model either including or not including the ‘FlavourEn’ column. I found that my validation f1 scores increased if I included this column. I would (given more time) also look at all of the other features, analyze them in more detail, and create models either including them or not, to see which features are actually predictive of fat level. For example, perhaps the feature ‘ManfacturerProvCode’ (which province a cheese was manufactured in) is not really predictive?

Another potential problem with creating these machine learning models is the fact that our dataset is actually not that large. Rather than having tens or hundreds of thousands of samples to train and validate on, we had 1042. This is quite a small dataset. I think that with a larger dataset, certain trends would become more evident, and more predictive. For example, perhaps the word “sharp” in the FlavourEn column would be predictive of lower fat cheeses, while “creamy” would be more predictive of higher fat cheeses? It would be interesting to add more data to our dataset and then try again to build a model and see if it is more predictive.

What was interesting during my analysis, is that I initially used RandomizedSearchCV to hyperparameter tune my models. It turned out that my default RandomForestClassifier performed better than my hyperparameter-tuned classifier! I decided that for tuning with only 2-3 parameters, the better choice would be to use GridSearchCV to more precisely tune. The hyperparameter-tuned RandomForestClassifier, after tuning using GridSearchCV DID perform better than the default RandomForestClassifier, but only on the test data, not the training data.

All in all, this was a good exercise to create a machine learning model… and a good demonstration that not all data can be used to create a model, and that not all data is predictive.
